88
00:03:42,060 --> 00:03:45,330
Right, let's move on to step two,

89
00:03:45,330 --> 00:03:48,330
which is to open and fund an account.

90
00:03:48,330 --> 00:03:49,740
When it comes to this step,

91
00:03:49,740 --> 00:03:52,770
there's one key decision
that many people overlook,

92
00:03:52,770 --> 00:03:54,333
a decision that can make

93
00:03:54,333 --> 00:03:56,550
or break your long-term results.

94
00:03:56,550 --> 00:04:00,120
And if you are taking on the
$5-a-day challenge like I am,

95
00:04:00,120 --> 00:04:02,640
this choice becomes even more critical.

96
00:04:02,640 --> 00:04:03,720
This is because the type

97
00:04:03,720 --> 00:04:05,940
of account you choose
will determine how much

98
00:04:05,940 --> 00:04:08,400
of your profits you
actually end up keeping.

99
00:04:08,400 --> 00:04:09,420
Let me explain.

100
00:04:09,420 --> 00:04:11,340
There are two main types of accounts

101
00:04:11,340 --> 00:04:12,540
we need to consider.

102
00:04:12,540 --> 00:04:17,540
For now, let's call them
account A and account B.

103
00:04:19,620 --> 00:04:23,160
Now, let's imagine we've
got $2,000 to invest.

104
00:04:23,160 --> 00:04:25,590
We'll split it equally between both boxes.

105
00:04:25,590 --> 00:04:28,410
So $1,000 goes into account A,

106
00:04:28,410 --> 00:04:31,410
and $1,000 goes into account B.

107
00:04:31,410 --> 00:04:33,780
At first, everything looks the same.

108
00:04:33,780 --> 00:04:36,510
Both accounts have the same
amount of money invested,

109
00:04:36,510 --> 00:04:39,210
but here's where things start to change.

110
00:04:39,210 --> 00:04:40,770
When you use account A,

111
00:04:40,770 --> 00:04:43,290
your profits aren't
entirely yours to keep,

112
00:04:43,290 --> 00:04:46,410
and that's because of the dreaded tax man.

113
00:04:46,410 --> 00:04:50,070
First, he takes a slice
of your dividend earnings.

114
00:04:50,070 --> 00:04:51,720
Dividends are like a reward

115
00:04:51,720 --> 00:04:53,430
companies give their shareholders.

116
00:04:53,430 --> 00:04:56,850
Now, not all companies
pay them, but many do.

117
00:04:56,850 --> 00:04:58,620
How much the tax man takes

118
00:04:58,620 --> 00:05:00,960
depends on your income and tax bracket,

119
00:05:00,960 --> 00:05:02,220
so the more you earn,

120
00:05:02,220 --> 00:05:03,930
the bigger the slice he takes.

121
00:05:03,930 --> 00:05:07,890
Next, he takes even more
for capital gains tax.

122
00:05:07,890 --> 00:05:09,870
This happens when you sell an investment

123
00:05:09,870 --> 00:05:11,190
for more than you paid for it.

124
00:05:11,190 --> 00:05:15,540
In the UK capital gains
tax is typically 10 to 20%.

125
00:05:15,540 --> 00:05:18,510
In the US, long-term
capital gains tax rates

126
00:05:18,510 --> 00:05:22,320
range from naught to 20%
based on your income level.

127
00:05:22,320 --> 00:05:24,990
Now, what about the money in account B?

128
00:05:24,990 --> 00:05:27,540
Well, this account has special protections

129
00:05:27,540 --> 00:05:29,730
that stop the tax man from reaching in

130
00:05:29,730 --> 00:05:31,200
and taking your profits.

131
00:05:31,200 --> 00:05:33,630
Everything you make here is yours to keep.

132
00:05:33,630 --> 00:05:36,120
That's because account B is known

133
00:05:36,120 --> 00:05:38,340
as a tax-advantaged account.

134
00:05:38,340 --> 00:05:42,210
Meanwhile, account A is just
a general investing account.

135
00:05:42,210 --> 00:05:43,560
In my humble opinion,

136
00:05:43,560 --> 00:05:46,260
you shouldn't even be looking
at a general investing account

137
00:05:46,260 --> 00:05:47,970
until you've fully taken advantage

138
00:05:47,970 --> 00:05:51,180
of everything a tax-advantaged
account has to offer.

139
00:05:51,180 --> 00:05:53,160
So how do you do that?

140
00:05:53,160 --> 00:05:55,050
Well, it depends on where you live.

141
00:05:55,050 --> 00:05:57,750
In the UK our tax-advantaged accounts

142
00:05:57,750 --> 00:05:59,670
are called stocks and shares ISAs,

143
00:05:59,670 --> 00:06:02,430
and in the US they're known as Roth IRAs.

144
00:06:02,430 --> 00:06:04,170
Both of these special accounts come

145
00:06:04,170 --> 00:06:06,150
with incredible tax benefits,

146
00:06:06,150 --> 00:06:08,760
but there are a few
things to keep in mind.

147
00:06:08,760 --> 00:06:10,920
In the UK you can contribute up

148
00:06:10,920 --> 00:06:14,220
to 20,000 pounds per year into an ISA.

149
00:06:14,220 --> 00:06:16,860
In the US Roth IRA contributions

150
00:06:16,860 --> 00:06:20,700
are capped at $6,500 each year

151
00:06:20,700 --> 00:06:24,360
or $7,500 if you're over 50.

152
00:06:24,360 --> 00:06:26,880
For most people, these limits are plenty,

153
00:06:26,880 --> 00:06:28,410
allowing you to build your future

154
00:06:28,410 --> 00:06:30,510
while still covering living expenses.

155
00:06:30,510 --> 00:06:34,320
The ISA allows you to withdraw
money at any time tax free,

156
00:06:34,320 --> 00:06:36,150
which makes it very flexible.

157
00:06:36,150 --> 00:06:37,800
So while a general investing account

158
00:06:37,800 --> 00:06:39,600
isn't necessarily a bad option,

159
00:06:39,600 --> 00:06:43,080
it often falls short when it
comes to maximizing your money.

160
00:06:43,080 --> 00:06:45,270
Of course, if a tax-advantaged account

161
00:06:45,270 --> 00:06:47,010
isn't available where you live,

162
00:06:47,010 --> 00:06:49,663
you'll have no other
choice but to use option A,

163
00:06:49,663 --> 00:06:52,170
a general investing account.

164
00:06:52,170 --> 00:06:55,830
I'm gonna use option B,
a stocks and shares ISA,

165
00:06:55,830 --> 00:06:58,170
because when we pull the
money out of this box

166
00:06:58,170 --> 00:06:59,280
at the end of the year,

167
00:06:59,280 --> 00:07:01,830
we want to keep as much as possible.

168
00:07:01,830 --> 00:07:03,000
As I mentioned earlier,

169
